I think this is a terrific idea.  I&#39;ve been wanting to find a way to support
the notion of &quot;expected failures&quot; to account for test-first unit testing,
and for future-work functional tests.  I was going to try to use an external
file listing the tests that can be expected to fail, and then writing a
TestListener or somesuch that checks the actual failures against the list.
This is clearly a much more elegant design.  (And it obeys OAOO!)

My only suggestion would be to a command line option (well, actually, an Ant
taskdef attribute :-) to specify whether or not the todos should be run.  If
they are run, report on the todos that (perhaps unexpectedly) passed, but
don&#39;t Go Red if any of them fail.

This would be extremely useful in my project, where we are using JUnit +
HttpUnit to build our suite of functional test.  Currently we can&#39;t &quot;work
ahead&quot; writing the functional tests since the unimplemented ones will break
the build!  I&#39;d like to simply ignore the todos when testing the
ContinuousIntegration build, but keep them enabled in the development
environment so the coders know what still needs to be done.

Thanks for the excellent idea!

.T.

Todd V. Jonker
Sr. Technical Associate
ZEFER Pittsburgh


&gt; Date: Mon, 12 Mar 2001 21:59:01 -0000
&gt; From: jcarpenter@...
&gt; Subject: todo tests in JUnit (think Perl)

&gt; We are finding that there are times when it may be desirable to check
&gt; into source control code that is not fully implemented.  The tests
&gt; may be defined, but the corresponding class implementation may not be
&gt; complete.
&gt; 
&gt; Perl&#39;s standard framework has the concept of a todo test.  A simple
&gt; enough way to notate such a test in JUnit would be to name a method
&gt; within a test todoBlah, rather than testBlah.  To safely go down this
&gt; road, it is desirable to extend JUnit to report on what todo tests
&gt; are in the code base in addition to the normal tests.  I am
&gt; considering writting such an extension and contributing it back to
&gt; the JUnit project.  Unfortuantely, I don&#39;t know where in the JUnit
&gt; code base to start.

